{
    "name": "Tallow Ooze",
    "type": "creature",
    "sections": [
        {
            "name": "Tallow Ooze",
            "type": "section",
            "sources": [
                {
                    "type": "source",
                    "name": "Pathfinder #154: Siege of the Dinosaurs",
                    "link": {
                        "type": "link",
                        "name": "Pathfinder #154: Siege of the Dinosaurs pg. 83",
                        "alt": "Pathfinder #154: Siege of the Dinosaurs pg. 83",
                        "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq0216l"
                    },
                    "page": 83
                }
            ],
            "html": "Pale yellow and smelling of meat, this unnatural, globular monster is composed entirely of rendered animal fat. A tallow ooze typically results from magical mishaps during the creation of enchanted candles or soaps, or while rendering the fat of a magical beast, though occasionally spellcasters create these beings intentionally.<br/><br/> A tallow ooze hunts other creatures to subsume them into its own body and absorb their fat. Since tallow is solid at room temperature, tallow oozes must metabolize their own bodies to produce enough heat to remain gelatinous. A tallow ooze that cannot replenish itself with absorbed fat will either consume itself or solidify, though a tallow ooze exposed to too much heat might melt entirely.<br/><br/><b><u><a aonid=\"5\" game-obj=\"Skills\" general=\"true\">Recall Knowledge - Ooze</a></u> (<u><a aonid=\"11\" game-obj=\"Skills\">Occultism</a></u>)</b>: DC 28"
        },
        {
            "name": "Ooze",
            "type": "section",
            "sections": [
                {
                    "name": "Amoebas Large and Small",
                    "type": "section",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Bestiary",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "alt": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01y0m?Pathfinder-Bestiary"
                            },
                            "page": 254
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "related_creatures",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Related Creatures",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Related Creatures",
                        "image": "Sidebar_4_RelatedCreatures.png"
                    },
                    "html": "<a aonid=\"751\" game-obj=\"Monsters\">Giant amoebas</a> and <a aonid=\"750\" game-obj=\"Monsters\">amoeba swarms</a> are usually found near each other, as the two oozes are part of the same life cycle. When a giant amoeba grows large enough, it can spontaneously split apart into two separate amoeba swarms, and when an amoeba swarm feeds enough, its individual components can fuse together into a single creature."
                },
                {
                    "name": "Oozing Acid",
                    "type": "section",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Bestiary",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "alt": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01y0m?Pathfinder-Bestiary"
                            },
                            "page": 254
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "additional_lore",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Additional Lore",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Additional Lore",
                        "image": "Sidebar_2_AdditionalLore.png"
                    },
                    "html": "Many oozes have acidic attacks that can quickly degrade flesh, wood, and even stronger materials. Some believe that oozes are the result of alchemical or magical experimentation run amok, while others postulate that they simply emerged from the natural processes of evolution."
                },
                {
                    "name": "Other Oozes",
                    "type": "section",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Bestiary",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "alt": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01y0m?Pathfinder-Bestiary"
                            },
                            "page": 254
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "related_creatures",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Related Creatures",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Related Creatures",
                        "image": "Sidebar_4_RelatedCreatures.png"
                    },
                    "html": "Many varieties of these nearly mindless predators exist in the world. Some are mere variants, with different colored puddings, jellies, and oozes with little to differentiate them from those presented here other than their habitat. Others are more specialized, or even dangerously intelligent. The <a aonid=\"368\" game-obj=\"Monsters\">shoggoth</a> is one such example, but another variety of deadly and powerful ooze is the thankfully rare blight, a creature composed of protoplasm and eyes that curses entire regions with its presence."
                }
            ],
            "sources": [
                {
                    "type": "source",
                    "name": "Bestiary",
                    "link": {
                        "type": "link",
                        "name": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                        "alt": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                        "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq01y0m?Pathfinder-Bestiary"
                    },
                    "page": 254
                }
            ],
            "html": "Slimes, molds, and other oozes can be found in dank dungeons and shadowed forests. While not necessarily evil, some grow to enormous sizes and have insatiable appetites."
        },
        {
            "name": "Saponaceous Tallow Ooze",
            "type": "section",
            "sources": [
                {
                    "type": "source",
                    "name": "Pathfinder #154: Siege of the Dinosaurs",
                    "link": {
                        "type": "link",
                        "name": "Pathfinder #154: Siege of the Dinosaurs pg. 83",
                        "alt": "Pathfinder #154: Siege of the Dinosaurs pg. 83",
                        "href": "https://paizo.com/products/btq0216l"
                    },
                    "page": 83
                }
            ],
            "subtype": "sidebar",
            "sidebar_type": "advice_and_rules",
            "sidebar_heading": "Advice and Rules",
            "image": {
                "type": "image",
                "name": "Advice and Rules",
                "image": "Sidebar_1_AdviceAndRules.png"
            },
            "html": "Exposure to a sufficient quantity of alkali (such as from ash) may cause a chemical reaction in a tallow ooze, turning it into a mass of living soap. Such saponaceous tallow oozes leave residual glycerol in their wake instead of grease (though the effects are the same) and gain the following ability. <br/><br/><b>Soapy Effluence</b> When a saponaceous tallow ooze is exposed to at least a gallon of water, takes damage from an ability with the water trait, or fails a saving throw against an effect with the <a aonid=\"165\" game-obj=\"Traits\">water</a> trait, it releases a cloud of bubbles that fills a 10-foot burst around the ooze\u2019s current space for 1 minute. Creatures within the area are <a aonid=\"7\" game-obj=\"Conditions\">dazzled</a>."
        }
    ],
